# Apps Web → Apps Docs

Any **new or materially changed** user-facing behavior in `apps/web` (routes, flows, config, **public HTTP API** under `apps/web/src/app/api/`, billing gates, AI features, auth) needs **matching updates** in `apps/docs` in the same change set. Do not merge web-only surface area without documentation.

## Audience separation — never mix

| Section | Path | Audience | Content |
|---------|------|----------|---------|
| **Product Guide** | `apps/docs/content/users/` | End users, customers, admins | Features, workflows, billing, troubleshooting, FAQ |
| **Developer Guide** | `apps/docs/content/developers/` | Contributors, integrators | Architecture, monorepo, local dev, testing, deployment, platforms |
| **API Reference** | `apps/docs/content/api/` | API consumers, MCP clients | REST endpoints, auth, errors, MCP tools, examples |

**Do not** put source code, repo paths, or deployment instructions in `users/`. **Do not** put end-user tutorials or marketing copy in `developers/` or `api/`. Cross-link between sections only when necessary (e.g. user billing page must not link to API auth docs).

## Layout (`apps/docs`)

- MDX lives under `apps/docs/content/`. Register pages in the nearest `_meta.ts` so the sidebar stays accurate.
- Top-level nav: `users/` (Product Guide), `developers/` (Developer Guide), `api/` (API Reference).
- **API** docs must document: route, method(s), auth, query/body fields, success `{ data }` / error `{ error }` envelope, relevant status codes, and pagination/CORS behavior where applicable (align with `.cursor/rules/public-api.mdc`).

## Rules

- If you touch `apps/web/src/app/api/**`, add or update docs under `apps/docs/content/api/` for every affected route.
- If you add a user-visible feature or change behavior, add or update pages under `apps/docs/content/users/`.
- If you change architecture, env vars, CI, or platform setup, update `apps/docs/content/developers/`.
- Keep copy honest about what is shipped; avoid "placeholder" language once the feature exists.
